uihRpuigxNKvzC_8pd2K7DeANhRsCSPuqyzNwsfd-PIhxKVSZZKArR5CckfymJBCmaxAbPbiRFXB3Qv36tf6S-wzCXcNuIQ3zJYxwZ_-OrGhGsvlz9UJ5g0mNqRHx8g3UVG97ySiuBrTn2lLICmU3Q2JDiORvPb7XrRcIP0D6Xsj7TYnFhvNfLqVXmVA2ebbjV2hvUZ71KhdMjMWcLu7-40g79eUslA8rYO22IBzWCYNDQKiLGxMuphOJd9uR-dftZu4R5hU_0p4CZkqHyyHBlb06bdlL6wh5ZXhPJ7FtWYrcuaJ1SFVZWoU5CXLWVbl-DddFAdVd9m-wmF6NqOHfFLtGK8XBmxQi5Xfsx9vh2Fb_3rHELQJ7-PZyqqlJWjyzPzDpDl73EuyYwADZN09FDTJQ8cHKHbaKcNgE3dkACNGF5e5XHcS8PRF9Rz1eV3PEN4PxX1beST8xEIz6GRqvw2MRVPQns67X6msx0W82z0YEcmM6PjBDAqoxxwoD57fdpFrGglNPI1BMyPePgxiox5WqJ-uFXs62cLEeEREICUyZbTnuycM3c8j0JA5OsjHEl8WDD3h3isfQnSze5ccTW9ZMYfeI9BatYjGS9-ArShrfbLHzOKCi9dtK5GNo2-ceK7gTg-I3fD1q_SnJXxtfqV5LMUbgtNWd8m_CEYGfrqnoz5y0Z05aHXAK4ybFtrw5IDA2jhOyf6bunNv77CreF98P43MabRVmqIs99_oMM2nfXNyaB_b-g0K2fqhzzp-lY8m-_VUcotU_zo4thUvx3VQptNmliHpW67thpyZZij4qHrLOdPSwD2iqLT-vBRpJkRJoAOxiBSi7Wq2FdVl8\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining testing approach**\\n\\nI need to focus on targeting the active class only. The previous method with dynamic class loading feels inappropriate. It might be better to create a simpler solution, like a separate \\\"forked JVM\\\" test that runs the adapter in a new Java process. However, I wonder about dynamic report generation from a native compile. It seems dynamic access call sites wouldn't work in a separate process without the JaCoCo agent. Improving line coverage by branch paths might be possible, but the report isn’t showing any lines.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering classpath order**\\n\\nI'm thinking that maybe the native image classpath orders dependencies before test classes. The build output shows `org/apache/xerces/parsers/DOMParser.class` being in the test. I’ll assert counters to prove that the stub was used; this also helps with the `getDocument` call using reflection. I should add counters to DOMParser and assert it in XML4J. However, I realize that this modifies the shared parser, which could affect the XercesDOMAdapter tests, but that's fine. It doesn’t cover line numbers, though.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating the coverage tool**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the coverage tool and how it relies on generated metadata, which means counters aren't really important—it's the behavior that matters more precisely. I plan to read the XercesDOMAdapter source since it likely uses the same parser with the namespace set to true. It looks like the counter assertion in XML4J might reset, so I need to add static counts to improve accuracy. Let's see how it all ties together!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_k3fjj5aBnuZ1Q0RFbDe80Rm3|fc_04d3a5750ac2288e0169fc84fe06cc8197aab0e7390263cebe", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge5/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/jdom/jdom/1.0b8/main/extracted/jdom-b8/src/java/org/jdom/adapters/XercesDOMAdapter.java", "limit": 160}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 875, "output": 1163, "cacheRead": 52736, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 54774, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778156777776, "responseId": "resp_04d3a5750ac2288e0169fc84eb1304819789d09f98cb1d9da2"}}
