[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Refining testing approach**\n\nI need to focus on targeting the active class only. The previous method with dynamic class loading feels inappropriate. It might be better to create a simpler solution, like a separate \"forked JVM\" test that runs the adapter in a new Java process. However, I wonder about dynamic report generation from a native compile. It seems dynamic access call sites wouldn't work in a separate process without the JaCoCo agent. Improving line coverage by branch paths might be possible, but the report isn’t showing any lines.\n\n**Considering classpath order**\n\nI'm thinking that maybe the native image classpath orders dependencies before test classes. The build output shows `org/apache/xerces/parsers/DOMParser.class` being in the test. I’ll assert counters to prove that the stub was used; this also helps with the `getDocument` call using reflection. I should add counters to DOMParser and assert it in XML4J. However, I realize that this modifies the shared parser, which could affect the XercesDOMAdapter tests, but that's fine. It doesn’t cover line numbers, though.\n\n**Evaluating the coverage tool**\n\nI'm thinking about the coverage tool and how it relies on generated metadata, which means counters aren't really important—it's the behavior that matters more precisely. I plan to read the XercesDOMAdapter source since it likely uses the same parser with the namespace set to true. It looks like the counter assertion in XML4J might reset, so I need to add static counts to improve accuracy. Let's see how it all ties together!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_04d3a5750ac2288e0169fc84ebfcb481979f310fe1df63c064\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_IT-bXEVULfBTujE2Pikspw8T5o3sia8zJFcIrLquwdM8UBNKnCW6-tGRxavA_VqXlSWrAFTcB1cepKNOuySWJIY_scVGn_4PLiNUFYwuXk6Xzx38Rj9U66xjqCuYPHBO4AYfm1Wjr9osntp9IAODrBKinmG6UIt-IX-fOmzpffUe95zNm